				<h1><a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/post/solution-creating-an-mpeg-with-mencoder-that-plays-on-windows-media-player">Solution: Creating an mpeg with mencoder that plays on Windows Media Player</a></h1>
				<div class="metaRight">
				<img src="../../wp-content/themes/colorbold/images/ico_user.png" alt="Author" /> <a href="../2007/01" title="Visit rechosen&#8217;s website" rel="external">rechosen</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="../../wp-content/themes/colorbold/images/ico_folder.png" alt="Category" /> <a href="../../category/solutions" title="View all posts in Solutions" rel="category tag">Solutions</a>	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="../../wp-content/themes/colorbold/images/ico_tag.png" alt="Tags" />  <a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/tag/mencoder" rel="nofollow tag">mencoder</a>, <a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/tag/mpeg" rel="nofollow tag">mpeg</a>, <a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/tag/windows-media-player" rel="nofollow tag">Windows Media Player</a></div>
				<p>This solution contains some options for the mencoder command that will result in an mpeg video file that will play on pretty much all players, even Windows Media Player. <a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/post/solution-creating-an-mpeg-with-mencoder-that-plays-on-windows-media-player#more-59" class="more-link">read more</a></p>
 
